You can make use of Extension Methods and write one.

Below returns true/false depending on if key is found or not.

    public static bool UpdateDictionaryAndGetOldValue(this Dictionary&lt;string, string&gt; dict, string key, string newVal, out string oldVal)
    {
        oldVal = string.Empty;
        if (dict.TryGetValue(key, out oldVal))
        {
            dict[key] = newVal;
            return true;
        }
        else
            return false;
    }

This returns the old value.

    public static string UpdateDictionaryAndGetOldValue(this Dictionary&lt;string, string&gt; dict, string key, string newVal)
    {
        string oldVal = string.Empty;
        dict.TryGetValue(key, out oldVal);
        dict[key] = newVal;
        return oldVal;
    }

And `TK` and `TV` can be used to make this general.

    public static class DictionaryExtensions
    {
        public static TValue UpdateAndGet&lt;TKey, TValue&gt;(this Dictionary&lt;TKey, TValue&gt; dictionary, TKey key, TValue newVal)
        {
            TValue oldVal;
            dictionary.TryGetValue(key, out oldVal);
            dictionary[key] = newVal;

            return oldVal;
        }
    }

You can make use of the built in `AddOrUpdate` method of the &quot;thread-safe&quot; `ConcurrentDictionary&lt;TKey,TValue&gt;` class which inherits from `IDictionary&lt;TKey,TValue&gt;` like:

    public static ConcurrentDictionary&lt;string, Country&gt; countries = new ConcurrentDictionary&lt;string, Country&gt;();

    public void Main()
    {
        Country poland = new Country { Name = &quot;Poland&quot;, Capital = &quot;Krakow&quot; };
        countries[poland.Name] = poland; 
